Question 1

I expect that the data requires a transformation because the experiment will most likely cause a very drastic change in the flies, as mutations can be small or very large.

Question 2 - Untransformed data set

H0 The different levels of radation will not have an effect on the brisltes of the flies.

HA The different levels of radation will have an effect on the bristles.

##                        Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## factor(bristles$GEN)    4 1216.2  304.05   36.24 6.72e-09 ***
## factor(bristles$BLOCK)  5 1546.7  309.34   36.87 1.99e-09 ***
## Residuals              20  167.8    8.39                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Conclusion The HA is supported (F(4,20)=36.24).

Question 3

The homogeneity of variance seems to be well distributed as the data set makes a normal distribution shape.

unstandarizedPred <- predict(model_1)
unstandarizedRes <- resid(model_1)

standarizedPred <- (unstandarizedPred - mean(unstandarizedPred)) / sd(unstandarizedPred)
standarizedRes <- (unstandarizedRes - mean(unstandarizedRes)) / sd(unstandarizedRes)

hist(standarizedRes, freq = FALSE)
curve(dnorm, add = TRUE)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model_1)

Question 4 - Transformed data set: Square Root

##                        Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## factor(bristles$GEN)    4 20.534   5.134   57.38 1.12e-10 ***
## factor(bristles$BLOCK)  5 23.910   4.782   53.45 6.89e-11 ***
## Residuals              20  1.789   0.089                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Conclusion The HA is supported (F(4,20)=57.38). The distribution here also seem to be well as there is a normal distribution, and a flatter curve.

unstandarizedPred <- predict(model_2)
unstandarizedRes <- resid(model_2)

standarizedPred <- (unstandarizedPred - mean(unstandarizedPred)) / sd(unstandarizedPred)
standarizedRes <- (unstandarizedRes - mean(unstandarizedRes)) / sd(unstandarizedRes)

hist(standarizedRes, freq = FALSE)
curve(dnorm, add = TRUE)

Question 5 - Transformed data set: Natural Log

##                        Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)    
## factor(bristles$GEN)    4  7.176  1.7939   27.12 7.9e-08 ***
## factor(bristles$BLOCK)  5  7.125  1.4249   21.54 2.0e-07 ***
## Residuals              20  1.323  0.0662                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Conclusion The HA is supported (F(4,20)=27.12). The distribution here also seem to be well as there is a normal distribution, and one can see the flattest curve out of all three in this analysis.

unstandarizedPred <- predict(model_3)
unstandarizedRes <- resid(model_3)

standarizedPred <- (unstandarizedPred - mean(unstandarizedPred)) / sd(unstandarizedPred)
standarizedRes <- (unstandarizedRes - mean(unstandarizedRes)) / sd(unstandarizedRes)

hist(standarizedRes, freq = FALSE)

Final Figure

ggplot(bristles, aes(x=factor(GEN), y=bristles$NBRISTln)) +
            geom_boxplot() +
            xlab("UV Radation Level") +
            ylab("Bristle per Fly") +
            theme_classic()

Figure 1: The F(4,20) is 27.12, so it is statistically significant.
